        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Working Principle</h2>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed mb-4">
          An oil centrifuge works on the principle of differential settling using a high centrifugal force to separate oil from solid and liquid contaminants. The centrifuge exerts up to <strong>10,000 Gs of force</strong> to separate particles as small as <strong>1 micron</strong> from the oil. It also separates any immiscible liquid contaminants from the oil.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
          The high-speed rotation of the bowl creates an intense centrifugal field that accelerates the natural settling process by thousands of times. Heavier particles such as metal fines, carbon residue, and other solid contaminants are forced outward against the bowl wall, while the lighter clean oil moves toward the center of the bowl and exits the centrifuge. When water is present, it forms an intermediate layer between the solids and the clean oil due to its density being higher than oil but lower than the solid contaminants. This three-phase separation happens continuously as the oil flows through the centrifuge, allowing for uninterrupted processing of large volumes of oil.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Benefits -->
