      <!-- Examples -->
      <div id="examples" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Examples of Applications</h2>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] mb-6">The following are examples of real-world oil centrifuge applications.</p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#E8A317] pl-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Lube Oil</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              All types of lube oil, from steam turbine oil to engine lubricating oil, need purification from fine metal contaminants and occasionally moisture. An oil centrifuge is ideal for processing large volumes of lube oil to a high purity level without filters. Simultaneous removal of water is an added advantage. Centrifugal lube oil purification extends oil life significantly, reduces bearing wear, and minimizes unplanned equipment downtime. Whether installed as a kidney-loop polishing system or as an inline treatment unit, an oil centrifuge delivers consistently clean lube oil that meets or exceeds OEM specifications.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#E8A317] pl-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Diesel Fuel</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Diesel fuel stored in tanks has rust, sediment, and other contaminants along with water from condensation. An oil centrifuge installed in a kidney loop on the storage tank keeps the fuel's solids and liquid contaminants clean. Regular centrifugal processing of stored diesel fuel prevents injector damage, improves combustion efficiency, and ensures reliable engine performance. This is particularly critical for standby generator systems and marine diesel applications where fuel quality directly impacts operational readiness.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#E8A317] pl-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Fuel Oil</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Fuel oil is a common energy source for most power plants, and large marine engines need to be maintained free of contaminants. A fuel oil centrifuge is a reliable separating machine that removes all sludge and water from fuel oil to keep it usable. Heavy fuel oil in particular contains high levels of asphaltenes, catalyst fines, and water that must be removed before combustion. Oil centrifuges are the industry standard for fuel oil treatment in both land-based power plants and marine vessel engine rooms.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#E8A317] pl-5">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Cutting Oil</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              A wide variety of industries use cutting oil for various metal-forming applications. This oil picks up solid metal particles during processing. It is essential to remove these particles from the oil for its reuse. An oil centrifuge can separate <strong>0.5-micron metal particles</strong> from the oil, thus making the oil reusable and reducing replacement costs. By continuously removing metal fines and tramp oil from cutting fluid, centrifugal separation extends coolant life, improves surface finish quality, and reduces disposal costs associated with spent cutting fluids.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Costs -->
      <div id="costs" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Costs</h2>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] mb-6">We have broken down the cost of oil centrifuges into the following categories.</p>

        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Equipment Cost</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              A small 'manual clean' oil centrifuge with a processing capacity of 3 GPM is around <strong>$15K</strong> for the bare centrifuge, and a high capacity (100 GPM) costs over <strong>$120K</strong>. Remanufactured centrifuges typically cost around 60% of new centrifuges. Optional accessories add to the system cost and can be more than the bare centrifuge cost, depending on the options chosen. Common accessories include feed pumps, heaters, control panels, flow meters, and complete skid-mounted turnkey systems with all piping and instrumentation.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Operating Cost</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              The only operating cost of an oil centrifuge is the cost of electricity to drive the motor. Since the centrifuge is a mechanical separator, it does not use any media or replaceable elements that add to operating costs. Therefore, the typical <strong>operating cost per gallon of an oil centrifuge is a fraction of a cent!</strong> This makes centrifugal separation one of the most economical methods for continuous oil purification, especially when compared to filter systems that require regular media replacement and associated labor costs.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-2">Maintenance Cost</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed">
              Like most mechanical equipment, oil centrifuges require routine maintenance. The maintenance costs associated with an oil separator are for the spare parts. The frequency of maintenance depends on the application and type of centrifuge. Detailed cost estimates of <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/#maintenance-costs" class="text-[#E8A317] hover:underline font-medium">maintenance costs related to disc stack oil centrifuges are listed here</a>. Routine maintenance typically includes replacing O-rings, seals, and bearings at scheduled intervals. Proper preventive maintenance ensures long centrifuge life and consistent separation performance.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

